	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">For Stockton pet owners, a secure fence isn't just about property boundaries—it's about keeping beloved family members safe. Whether you have an athletic Labrador who can clear a 4-foot fence or a determined terrier who loves to dig, the right fencing solution ensures your pets enjoy outdoor time safely. This guide covers everything you need to know about pet-proof fencing in Stockton's unique environment.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>Understanding Your Pet's Escape Tactics</h2>
	<p>Before choosing a fence, understand how different pets attempt to escape. This knowledge helps you select the right solution for your specific situation.</p>

	<h3>The Jumpers</h3>
	<p>Many dogs can jump surprisingly high. Athletic breeds like Border Collies, Australian Shepherds, and Pit Bulls can clear 4-5 feet easily. Even medium-sized dogs can launch themselves over fences when motivated by squirrels, other animals, or separation anxiety.</p>

	<h3>The Diggers</h3>
	<p>Terriers, Beagles, Huskies, and many other breeds have strong digging instincts. Given Stockton's relatively soft soil (especially after irrigation), determined diggers can tunnel under a fence within hours if proper barriers aren't installed.</p>

	<h3>The Climbers</h3>
	<p>Chain link fences are essentially ladders for dogs with climbing instincts. Breeds like Huskies, Australian Cattle Dogs, and even some Pit Bulls can scale chain link fences with ease.</p>

	<h3>The Squeezers</h3>
	<p>Smaller dogs and puppies can exploit surprisingly small gaps. Spaces between pickets, gaps at gates, or openings where terrain is uneven create escape routes for determined small pets.</p>

	<h2>Recommended Fence Heights by Dog Size</h2>

