	<p><strong>Note:</strong> Stockton municipal code typically allows 6-foot fences in backyards without permits. Heights above 6 feet may require permits and approval.</p>

	<h2>Best Fence Materials for Dogs</h2>

	<h3>Wood Privacy Fencing</h3>
	<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Blocks visual stimulation that triggers barking and escape attempts</li>
		<li>No footholds for climbing</li>
		<li>Attractive appearance that complements Stockton homes</li>
		<li>Can be built to any height</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Dogs may chew on wood (especially puppies)</li>
		<li>Gaps can develop as wood ages in Stockton's dry climate</li>
		<li>Higher maintenance than other options</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Dogs motivated by visual stimuli, medium to large breeds</p>

	<h3>Vinyl Privacy Fencing</h3>
	<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Smooth surface prevents climbing</li>
		<li>No splinters or toxic materials for chewing dogs</li>
		<li>Withstands Stockton heat without warping</li>
		<li>Easy to clean when dogs jump against it</li>
		<li>Maintains appearance for decades</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Higher initial cost than wood</li>
		<li>Limited color options</li>
		<li>Can crack under extreme impact</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Dogs who chew or scratch at fences, hot climate durability</p>

	<h3>Chain Link with Privacy Slats</h3>
	<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Affordable option for large yards</li>
		<li>Durable and long-lasting</li>
		<li>Privacy slats reduce visual triggers</li>
		<li>Good airflow in Stockton heat</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Climb-able without modifications</li>
		<li>Dogs can push through or damage mesh</li>
		<li>Less aesthetically pleasing</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Non-climbing dogs, budget-conscious large property enclosures</p>

	<h3>Ornamental Iron/Aluminum</h3>
	<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Extremely durable and strong</li>
		<li>Can't be chewed through</li>
		<li>Long lifespan in all conditions</li>
		<li>Elegant appearance</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Gaps between pickets allow small dogs to squeeze through</li>
		<li>Provides visual access to stimuli</li>
		<li>Can be climbed by some dogs</li>
		<li>Higher cost</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large dogs, combined with additional barriers for small dogs</p>

	<h2>Anti-Dig Solutions</h2>
	<p>Stockton's soil conditions make digging relatively easy for dogs. Here are proven solutions:</p>

	<h3>Buried Wire Mesh</h3>
	<p>Installing galvanized wire mesh (hardware cloth) buried 6-12 inches below ground level and extending outward prevents digging under the fence. This is the most effective permanent solution.</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Installation:</strong> Bury mesh in an L-shape—12 inches down and 12 inches out from fence</li>
		<li><strong>Material:</strong> Use 12-14 gauge galvanized wire for durability</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> Adds $3-5 per linear foot to installation</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Concrete Footer</h3>
	<p>A poured concrete footer along the fence line creates an impenetrable barrier. This premium solution is especially effective for determined diggers.</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Specifications:</strong> 4-6 inches wide, 6-12 inches deep</li>
		<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Permanent solution, also prevents fence post heaving</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> Adds $8-15 per linear foot</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Gravel Barriers</h3>
	<p>A 6-inch wide strip of large gravel or river rock along the fence line discourages digging. Dogs dislike digging in loose rocks.</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Installation:</strong> Dig a 6-inch deep trench, fill with 3-4 inch diameter rocks</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> May need periodic replenishment</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $2-4 per linear foot DIY</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Landscape Timbers</h3>
	<p>Pressure-treated landscape timbers laid along the fence base create a visual and physical barrier that discourages digging.</p>

	<h2>Anti-Climb Solutions</h2>

	<h3>Coyote Rollers</h3>
	<p>Spinning rollers mounted on top of the fence prevent dogs (and coyotes) from gaining purchase to pull themselves over. When a dog tries to grab the top, the roller spins, causing them to fall back.</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Installation:</strong> Mount brackets and aluminum or PVC rollers along fence top</li>
		<li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> Excellent for athletic jumpers and climbers</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $5-15 per linear foot</li>
		<li><strong>Bonus:</strong> Also keeps coyotes OUT—important in Stockton's semi-rural areas</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Fence Extensions</h3>
	<p>Adding height to existing fences can deter jumping. Options include:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Lattice toppers:</strong> Add 1-2 feet of lattice (note: may be climb-able)</li>
		<li><strong>Angled extensions:</strong> 45-degree inward-angled sections prevent jumping</li>
		<li><strong>Privacy slat extensions:</strong> For chain link, add height with privacy slats</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Removing Launch Points</h3>
	<p>Dogs often use objects near the fence to gain height. Ensure nothing near the fence provides a jumping platform:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Move furniture, dog houses, and planters away from fence lines</li>
		<li>Trim tree branches that overhang near the fence</li>
		<li>Address terrain changes that create launch points</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Gate Security for Pets</h2>
	<p>Gates are often the weak point in pet containment. Ensure yours are escape-proof:</p>

	<h3>Gate Height Matching</h3>
	<p>Gates should be the same height as your fence. Shorter gates create easy escape points.</p>

	<h3>Gap Elimination</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Install gap-filling strips at the bottom of gates</li>
		<li>Ensure latches create tight closure with no gaps</li>
		<li>Check hinges for spacing that allows squeezing</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Secure Latches</h3>
	<p>Many dogs learn to open simple latches. Consider:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Self-closing hinges:</strong> Ensures gates always return to closed position</strong></li>
		<li><strong>Gravity latches:</strong> Automatically engage when gate closes</li>
		<li><strong>Keyed locks:</strong> Prevent children and clever dogs from opening</li>
		<li><strong>Double-gate systems:</strong> Airlock-style entry prevents escapes during entry/exit</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Protecting Dogs from Stockton's Climate</h2>
	<p>Beyond containment, consider your dog's comfort in Stockton's hot summers:</p>

	<h3>Shade Considerations</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Solid privacy fences create shade on one side—orient accordingly</li>
		<li>Ensure dogs have access to shaded areas during hot months</li>
		<li>Consider awnings or shade cloth attachments to fence sections</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Hot Surface Warning</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Metal fences can become extremely hot in summer sun</li>
		<li>Dark-colored fences absorb more heat</li>
		<li>Consider lighter colors or heat-reflective coatings</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Visibility for Heat Monitoring</h3>
	<p>While privacy fences are great for containment, ensure you can visually check on pets. Consider adding viewing windows or using fence designs that allow monitoring from inside.</p>

	<h2>Multi-Pet Households</h2>
	<p>Homes with multiple pets may need additional considerations:</p>

	<h3>Different Size Dogs</h3>
	<p>When you have both large and small dogs, fence for the most challenging scenario. If your large dog jumps and small dog squeezes, you need height AND gap prevention.</p>

	<h3>Dogs and Cats Together</h3>
	<p>Keeping cats contained requires additional measures:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>6-foot minimum fence height</li>
		<li>Inward-angled extensions or cat-proof rollers</li>
		<li>No horizontal rails or footholds for climbing</li>
		<li>Consider enclosed "catios" for guaranteed containment</li>
	</ul>

